United States changes visa rules
People will have to turn to the Centres of the Service for visa applicants before interviewing the Consular Department; costs will be lower and the waiting time will be shorter.
As from 10 January 2011, the process of processing visas at the Embassy of the United States and consulates will be amended.
with a new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Centres of the Service for Visa Applicants (ASC) before interviewing the Consular Department.
Staff from the ASC will receive biometric information from the applicant and will be evaluated by the Consular Department prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, among which are the following:
The total cost of issuing a visa will be lower, no fee will be necessary for the appointment, the second for processing the application and the other for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee to cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: $140 per tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including temporary staff visa) and $390 per visa for traders and investors.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only turn to the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Given that biometric information will be collected in the ASC, applicants who will require a second interview at the Consular Department will spend less time than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for visas at consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra fee for the service of $26.
For further information on the new procedure for the visa application, please visit the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boltines/sp1012001_Visas-FAQs.html
