World Light Restoration Plan
Yesterday in Cancún, the UN proposed a plan to restore domestic lighting, lighting and industrial space in 100 countries in order to achieve a greenhouse effect (GES), which corresponds to almost one third of the further restrictions to be achieved to stabilise the planet's climate from now on to 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to push into Cancún to compensate for the absence of difficult-to-realizable commitments to reduce on the part of industrially advanced countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the light bulbs, which monopolize 50 to 70% of the market, are replaced by fluorescent lamps or, even better, electric-luminescence diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), a substantial amount of 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet caused by lighting would be discarded.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of the world's emissions.
It's the equivalent of 70% of emissions from a car park across the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, among them Canada, were involved in voluntary reduction plans that should allow for the reduction of global emissions of GES from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract 5 Gt from this balance sheet in order to achieve climate stabilisation at 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In hot bulbs 95% of the energy is dispersed in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, is the product of light.
With fluorescent lamps, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new DEL bulbs, we will reduce this consumption twice more.
Flu compact bulbs last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
New bulbs with DEL, such as Philips - this company reportedly participated in the UN study - have an estimated life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a hot bulb, which gives us an idea of a possible savings with a plan of compensation that would be applied in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with reostats and radiate less heat.
