Climate: how France hacked its promises of financing
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to try to keep promises for quickly unblocked financing (fast start or early start funding) implemented by developed countries.
And the big French hacks were discovered
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union has pledged 7.2 billion euros for three years and France 1.26 billion euros (that is 420 million per year).
At the start of COP16, the EU drew up a large essay to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to finance a fast start: a report clarifying the action of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparent operations are invaluable and valued at their true value: advanced countries and civil society would want all developed countries and civil society to do the same with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, leading it on the right path to meeting its promise of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
These funds are "new and additional" under the Copenhagen Agreement to ensure that the increased burden is realized without prejudice to public development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no match for what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered the 2009 reference: international funding has been retained and it adds 150 million to it for three years the title of fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment dates or deadlines at the level of public development aid.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of public aid for the development of d'Aide publice au développement.
Specifically, the total amount of France's support to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease), to meet its commitment to finance "new and additional" ...
Another crucial element is the distribution of gifts and loans.
There's no rule there yet, and everyone chooses their own way of calculating it.
Some people, like France, think that 1€ of the loan is equal to 1€ of the donation.
Obviously, this is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be proved for certain investments that are profitable (often related to projects linked to the reduction of emissions consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as equivalent to one euro that we give... , we should not understand it as the title of our liabilities but as the price of the loan for the creditor country (i.e. the equivalent of interest rates).
But France can only provide the following justification: it "obsesses" its commitment of EUR 420 million, of which it makes 91.5% of the loan (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of the gifts (EUR 36.1 million) - see EU document to verify it for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that makes use of the loan to that extent.
Germany has requested 46% of these, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) comply with their commitments with 100% of the gifts.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives 1€ to meet its promise, France will only give 10 cents and consider this effort comparable.
That's a beautiful kale piece!
For the sake of summary, in its funding "fast start" France operates with a double shedding: on the one hand with the development of the stock in time and on the other hand with a real financial burden.
Although it only spends 36.1m euros, it can convince that it is issuing 420m euros "new and additional" in relation to its promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that although it is Bertie who made such a decision) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would Member States continue to donate if only to borrow?) and when negotiating, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The chapter on early financing is only a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate debates.
But it could be a grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw lessons from this first year of early funding.
First, France should notify the change in its way of keeping the accounts for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of compliance with its obligations and fairness and justice to the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should prevent the debate on deposits to long-term financing (the other main chapter currently under discussion): we will not avoid the question of 'addictivity' or the way in which loans are accounted for.
France should change its position in order to become as progressive with these deposits as it is with others.
So everyone is putting their hopes in the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Koscius-Morizet, who is coming to Cancún next week.
The surprising announcement of the fast start of France and its vision of "addictivity" and the use of loans could raise the level of international confidence necessary to further advance the discussions.
